TY  - JOUR
T1  - Asymmetric Growth and Institutions in an Interdependent World
AU  - Acemoglu, Daron
AU  - Robinson, James A.
AU  - Verdier, Thierry
Y1  - 2017/05/26
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693038
DO  - 10.1086/693038
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1245
EP  - 1305
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We present a model of technologically interconnected countries that benefit and potentially contribute to advances in the world technology frontier. Greater inequality between successful and unsuccessful entrepreneurs increases entrepreneurial effort and a country?s contribution to that frontier. Under plausible assumptions, the world equilibrium is asymmetric, involving different economic institutions and technology levels for different countries. Some countries become technology leaders and opt for a type of ?cutthroat? capitalism with greater inequality and innovations, while others free ride on the cutthroat incentives of the leaders and choose a more ?cuddly? form of capitalism with greater social insurance for entrepreneurs.
AB  - We present a model of technologically interconnected countries that benefit and potentially contribute to advances in the world technology frontier. Greater inequality between successful and unsuccessful entrepreneurs increases entrepreneurial effort and a country?s contribution to that frontier. Under plausible assumptions, the world equilibrium is asymmetric, involving different economic institutions and technology levels for different countries. Some countries become technology leaders and opt for a type of ?cutthroat? capitalism with greater inequality and innovations, while others free ride on the cutthroat incentives of the leaders and choose a more ?cuddly? form of capitalism with greater social insurance for entrepreneurs.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693038
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693038
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Gender Gaps in Performance: Evidence from Young Lawyers
AU  - Azmat, Ghazala
AU  - Ferrer, Rosa
Y1  - 2017/06/23
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693686
DO  - 10.1086/693686
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1306
EP  - 1355
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper documents the gender gap in performance among high-skilled professionals in the United States. On the basis of widely used performance measures in law firms, we find that male lawyers bill 10 percent more hours and bring in more than twice as much new client revenue as female lawyers. The differential impact across genders in the presence of young children and differences in aspirations to become a law firm partner account for a large share of the difference in performance. We show that accounting for performance has important consequences for gender gaps in lawyers? earnings and subsequent promotion.
AB  - This paper documents the gender gap in performance among high-skilled professionals in the United States. On the basis of widely used performance measures in law firms, we find that male lawyers bill 10 percent more hours and bring in more than twice as much new client revenue as female lawyers. The differential impact across genders in the presence of young children and differences in aspirations to become a law firm partner account for a large share of the difference in performance. We show that accounting for performance has important consequences for gender gaps in lawyers? earnings and subsequent promotion.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693686
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693686
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - International Trade, Technology, and the Skill Premium
AU  - Burstein, Ariel
AU  - Vogel, Jonathan
Y1  - 2017/06/08
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693373
DO  - 10.1086/693373
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1356
EP  - 1412
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - What are the consequences of international trade on the skill premium? We incorporate skill-intensity differences across firms and sectors into a standard model of international trade. Reductions in trade costs reallocate factors toward a country's comparative advantage sectors, increasing the skill premium in countries with a comparative advantage in skill-intensive sectors and decreasing it elsewhere. Reductions in trade costs also reallocate factors toward more productive and skill-intensive firms within sectors and toward skill-intensive sectors in all countries, increasing the skill premium in all countries. Quantitatively, we find that trade liberalization increases the skill premium in almost all countries.
AB  - What are the consequences of international trade on the skill premium? We incorporate skill-intensity differences across firms and sectors into a standard model of international trade. Reductions in trade costs reallocate factors toward a country's comparative advantage sectors, increasing the skill premium in countries with a comparative advantage in skill-intensive sectors and decreasing it elsewhere. Reductions in trade costs also reallocate factors toward more productive and skill-intensive firms within sectors and toward skill-intensive sectors in all countries, increasing the skill premium in all countries. Quantitatively, we find that trade liberalization increases the skill premium in almost all countries.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693373
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693373
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Precommitments for Financial Self-Control? Micro Evidence from the 2003 Korean Credit Crisis
AU  - Cho, SungJin
AU  - Rust, John
Y1  - 2017/05/26
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693037
DO  - 10.1086/693037
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1413
EP  - 1464
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We analyze high-frequency micro panel data on customers of a major Korean credit card company before and after the 2003 Korean credit crisis and find evidence of pervasive precommitment behavior that is difficult to explain using standard economic theories: (1) customers voluntarily reduce their credit card borrowing limits without any compensation, (2) customers turn down interest-free installment loan offers with high probability, and (3) of the small fraction of customers who do accept interest-free loan offers, most precommit to pay off the loan over a shorter term than the maximum allowed term under the offer.
AB  - We analyze high-frequency micro panel data on customers of a major Korean credit card company before and after the 2003 Korean credit crisis and find evidence of pervasive precommitment behavior that is difficult to explain using standard economic theories: (1) customers voluntarily reduce their credit card borrowing limits without any compensation, (2) customers turn down interest-free installment loan offers with high probability, and (3) of the small fraction of customers who do accept interest-free loan offers, most precommit to pay off the loan over a shorter term than the maximum allowed term under the offer.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693037
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693037
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Smoking, Expectations, and Health: A Dynamic Stochastic Model of Lifetime Smoking Behavior
AU  - Darden, Michael
Y1  - 2017/06/09
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693394
DO  - 10.1086/693394
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1465
EP  - 1522
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I estimate a dynamic, stochastic model of smoking, expectations, and health that makes explicit channels through which an individual may learn about the health risks of smoking. Simulations of the structural model suggest that cardiovascular biomarker information at repeated health exams does not significantly alter smoking behavior because (a) signals of biomarker health are noisy within individuals, (b) the influence of biomarkers on major health outcomes is small, and (c) cigarette smoking is addictive. This paper also presents evidence of selection in smoking that, when not modeled, may cause an overstatement of the effect of smoking on expected longevity.
AB  - I estimate a dynamic, stochastic model of smoking, expectations, and health that makes explicit channels through which an individual may learn about the health risks of smoking. Simulations of the structural model suggest that cardiovascular biomarker information at repeated health exams does not significantly alter smoking behavior because (a) signals of biomarker health are noisy within individuals, (b) the influence of biomarkers on major health outcomes is small, and (c) cigarette smoking is addictive. This paper also presents evidence of selection in smoking that, when not modeled, may cause an overstatement of the effect of smoking on expected longevity.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693394
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693394
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Contests for Experimentation
AU  - Halac, Marina
AU  - Kartik, Navin
AU  - Liu, Qingmin
Y1  - 2017/05/26
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693040
DO  - 10.1086/693040
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1523
EP  - 1569
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study contests for innovation with learning about the innovation?s feasibility and opponents? outcomes. We characterize contests that maximize innovation when the designer chooses a prize-sharing scheme and a disclosure policy. A ?public winner-takes-all? contest dominates public contests?where any success is immediately disclosed?with any other prize-sharing scheme as well as winner-takes-all contests with any other disclosure policy. Yet, jointly modifying prize sharing and disclosure can increase innovation. In a broad class of mechanisms, it is optimal to share the prize with disclosure following a certain number of successes; under simple conditions, a ?hidden equal-sharing? contest is optimal.
AB  - We study contests for innovation with learning about the innovation?s feasibility and opponents? outcomes. We characterize contests that maximize innovation when the designer chooses a prize-sharing scheme and a disclosure policy. A ?public winner-takes-all? contest dominates public contests?where any success is immediately disclosed?with any other prize-sharing scheme as well as winner-takes-all contests with any other disclosure policy. Yet, jointly modifying prize sharing and disclosure can increase innovation. In a broad class of mechanisms, it is optimal to share the prize with disclosure following a certain number of successes; under simple conditions, a ?hidden equal-sharing? contest is optimal.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693040
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693040
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Delayed Overshooting: Is It an ’80s Puzzle?
AU  - Kim, Seong-Hoon
AU  - Moon, Seongman
AU  - Velasco, Carlos
Y1  - 2017/06/08
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693372
DO  - 10.1086/693372
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1570
EP  - 1598
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We reinvestigate the delayed overshooting puzzle. Using a method of sign restrictions, we find that delayed overshooting is primarily a phenomenon of the 1980s when the Fed was under the chairmanship of Paul Volcker. Related findings are as follows: (1) Uncovered interest parity fails to hold during the Volcker era and tends to hold during the post-Volcker era; (2) US monetary policy shocks have substantial impacts on exchange rate variations but misleadingly appear to have small impacts when monetary policy regimes are pooled. In brief, we confirm Dornbusch?s overshooting hypothesis.
AB  - We reinvestigate the delayed overshooting puzzle. Using a method of sign restrictions, we find that delayed overshooting is primarily a phenomenon of the 1980s when the Fed was under the chairmanship of Paul Volcker. Related findings are as follows: (1) Uncovered interest parity fails to hold during the Volcker era and tends to hold during the post-Volcker era; (2) US monetary policy shocks have substantial impacts on exchange rate variations but misleadingly appear to have small impacts when monetary policy regimes are pooled. In brief, we confirm Dornbusch?s overshooting hypothesis.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693372
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693372
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Democratic Weights of Nations
AU  - Kurz, Sascha
AU  - Maaser, Nicola
AU  - Napel, Stefan
Y1  - 2017/05/26
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693039
DO  - 10.1086/693039
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1599
EP  - 1634
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Which voting weights ought to be allocated to single delegates of differently sized groups from a democratic fairness perspective? We operationalize the one person, one vote principle by demanding every individual?s influence on collective decisions to be equal a priori. The analysis differs from previous ones by considering intervals of alternatives. New reasons lead to an old conclusion: weights should be proportional to the square root of constituency sizes if voter preferences are independent and identically distributed. This finding is fragile, however, in that preference polarization along constituency lines quickly calls for plain proportionality.
AB  - Which voting weights ought to be allocated to single delegates of differently sized groups from a democratic fairness perspective? We operationalize the one person, one vote principle by demanding every individual?s influence on collective decisions to be equal a priori. The analysis differs from previous ones by considering intervals of alternatives. New reasons lead to an old conclusion: weights should be proportional to the square root of constituency sizes if voter preferences are independent and identically distributed. This finding is fragile, however, in that preference polarization along constituency lines quickly calls for plain proportionality.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693039
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693039
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Taxation and the Allocation of Talent
AU  - Lockwood, Benjamin B.
AU  - Nathanson, Charles G.
AU  - Weyl, E. Glen
Y1  - 2017/06/09
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693393
DO  - 10.1086/693393
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1635
EP  - 1682
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Taxation affects the allocation of talented individuals across professions by blunting material incentives and thus magnifying nonpecuniary incentives of pursuing a ?calling.? Estimates from the literature suggest that high-paying professions have negative externalities, whereas low-paying professions have positive externalities. A calibrated model therefore prescribes negative marginal tax rates on middle-class incomes and positive rates on the rich. The welfare gains from implementing such a policy are small and are dwarfed by the gains from profession-specific taxes and subsidies. These results depend crucially on externality estimates and labor substitution patterns across professions, both of which are very uncertain given existing empirical evidence.
AB  - Taxation affects the allocation of talented individuals across professions by blunting material incentives and thus magnifying nonpecuniary incentives of pursuing a ?calling.? Estimates from the literature suggest that high-paying professions have negative externalities, whereas low-paying professions have positive externalities. A calibrated model therefore prescribes negative marginal tax rates on middle-class incomes and positive rates on the rich. The welfare gains from implementing such a policy are small and are dwarfed by the gains from profession-specific taxes and subsidies. These results depend crucially on externality estimates and labor substitution patterns across professions, both of which are very uncertain given existing empirical evidence.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693393
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693393
Y2  - 2024/03/17
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Does Transparency Lead to Pay Compression?
AU  - Mas, Alexandre
Y1  - 2017/06/02
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/693137
DO  - 10.1086/693137
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1683
EP  - 1721
VL  - 125
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper asks whether pay disclosure in the public sector changes wage setting at the top of the distribution. I examine a 2010 California mandate that required municipal salaries to be posted online. Among top managers, disclosure led to approximately 7 percent average compensation declines, and a 75 percent increase in their quit rate, relative to managers in cities that had already disclosed salaries. The wage cuts were largely nominal. Wage cuts were larger in cities with higher initial compensation, but not in cities where compensation was initially out of line with (measured) fundamentals. The response is more consistent with public aversion to high compensation than the effects of increased accountability.
AB  - This paper asks whether pay disclosure in the public sector changes wage setting at the top of the distribution. I examine a 2010 California mandate that required municipal salaries to be posted online. Among top managers, disclosure led to approximately 7 percent average compensation declines, and a 75 percent increase in their quit rate, relative to managers in cities that had already disclosed salaries. The wage cuts were largely nominal. Wage cuts were larger in cities with higher initial compensation, but not in cities where compensation was initially out of line with (measured) fundamentals. The response is more consistent with public aversion to high compensation than the effects of increased accountability.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/693137
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/693137
Y2  - 2024/03/17
